snippet.textDisplay: Boris sounds good.  I wish him well.  I remember when he first won big.  He said it was lonely.  Few around.  His peers off playing in another tournament.  I felt bad hearing the sadness in his voice.  I had a child playing junior tennis and knew it was indeed a lonely sport.  I was hoping other professional players would have rallied around Becker when he needed it. They did not. Much like Steffi did not rally around Monica when she was stabbed.  I have always liked Djokovic.

snippet.textDisplay: Boris is right about everything (including that, clearly and beyond argument, Djokovic is the GOAT) except about popularity.  Roger is and will remain the King in most fans's hearts.  He just has a certain _je ne sais quoi_ ... an aura ... a presence that Novak (or perhaps anyone else) will not be able to come close to.  This will not change even if Djokovic wins 30 slams (I don't see him winning even one more -- age has finally caught up) and it will not even be close.  Perhaps unfair because Novak seems to be a truly incredible person and champion but that's that.

snippet.textDisplay: I absolutely love Boris Becker, I also admire and respect the great Djokovic, both men are supreme athletes who achieved an awful lot within their respective eras and generations, however I will never regard Novak as being greater than either Rafa or Roger, Roger in particular is the greatest tennis player of all the big four and everyone else he faced, but I believe the greatest player of all time is Shingo Kunieda, he was a wheelchair player who won 4 Paralympic gold medals 🥇, 50 grand slams which includes a record 28 singles titles (more than Novak, more than Rafa and more than Roger), think what you may but that is my belief
